{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470908"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:42:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:42:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"72"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/72"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.06,0.66,0.01,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"72"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113390"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/72"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"72"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95411"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11505"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2920"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46894"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113390"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 7-year-old boy is brought by his mother to the Emergency Department with a three hour history of cough and worsening wheeze. He has asthma and hay fever and his current symptoms have persisted and worsened despite using salbutamol every three hours as instructed in his asthma action plan. In the last few hours, he has been using it every two hours. He appears tired, breathless and cannot speak in full sentences, and has both subcostal and intercostal recessions. On examination his blood pressure is 100/80 mmHg, pulse 110/min, temperature 37.2C, respiratory rate 28/min and SpO2 92% on room air. Chest auscultation reveals widespread wheeze and no other abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to oxygen, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV magnesium sulfate","0.5ml of IM adrenaline in a ratio of 1:1000","Salbutamol and ipratropium via MDI and spacer","Oral montelukast","Oral prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child is almost certainly having an acute asthma exacerbation. The severity of this child\u2019s acute asthma, according to the Australian Asthma Handbook classification for children 6 years and older, is classified as\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Esevere due to the presence of any of the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAppearing tired\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnable to speak full sentences\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESigns of increased respiratory effort, such as subcostal and intercostal recessions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERespiratory rate \u0026gt; 25 breaths/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeart rate \u2265 110/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOxygen saturation 90-94%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt should be noted that the presence of a wheeze is not a marker of severity, and that a silent chest or reduced air entry is a sign of life-threatening asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst anaphylaxis should be considered as a differential in those presenting with severe asthma, the lack of involvement of two systems (dermatological, gastrointestinal, respiratory or cardiovascular) means that this patients presentation is not consistent with anaphylaxis. Therefore, use of \u003Cstrong\u003EIM adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe will need a systemic steroid (\u003Cstrong\u003Eprednisolone) \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich should be administered within the first hour of presentation, however this is not the first-line management. The first line of management for severe asthma in children 6 yeras and older is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E12 puffs of \u003Cstrong\u003Esalbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E (due to his age being \u0026gt;6 years) via MDI and spacer, repeated every 20 minutes over one hour, with four breaths in between each puff\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E8 puffs of \u003Cstrong\u003Eipratropium\u003C/strong\u003E via pressurised metered-dose inhaler and spacer, every 20 minutes for the first hour. Repeat 4-6 hourly for 24 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis treatment is often referred to as \u0022burst therapy\u0022 and is often highly effective. This is often administered via an MDI with spacer (and in young children the addition of a facemask) but it can also be administered via nebuliser when oxygen is also required. It is important to note that self administered salbutamol pre-hospital would be largely ineffective at managing severe acute asthma attacks due to inadequate dosing and frequency and therefore escalation to the above treatment is required. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral leukotriene receptor antagonists, \u003Cstrong\u003Emontelukast\u003C/strong\u003E, are not indicated in the management of acute asthma. They can be used as a preventer for chronic asthma, particularly those with allergic triggers. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV magnesium sulfate\u003C/strong\u003E is used as a second-line bronchodilator in severe or life-threatening acute asthma, or when poor response to repeated maximal doses of other bronchodilators. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["After oxygen, salbutamol inhalation should be the next step in management of an acute episode of asthma."],"references":["Wu TD, Brigham EP, McCormack MC. Asthma in the Primary Care Setting. Med Clin N Am. 2019; 103:435-52.","Australian Asthma Handbook. [cited 2021Jun12]. Available from: https://www.asthmahandbook.org.au/acute-asthma/clinical/bronchodilators","Australian Asthma Handbook. [cited 2021Jun12]. Available from: https://www.asthmahandbook.org.au/acute-asthma/clinical/secondary-assessment","Australian Asthma Handbook. [cited 2021Jun21]. Available from: https://www.asthmahandbook.org.au/acute-asthma/clinical/add-on-treatment"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95411"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"72"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95411"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-11T21:01:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-11T21:02:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"72"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113390"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"